Complex Function: The H+/K+-ATPase functions as the gastric proton pump;  responsible for gastric acid secretion in the stomach. It exchanges hydrogen ions (H+) for potassium ions (K+) across the parietal cell membrane;  creating the acidic environment in the stomach lumen with pH values as low as 0.8-1.0. This acidic environment is essential for protein digestion;  nutrient absorption;  and protection against ingested pathogens. The complex hydrolyzes ATP to provide energy for the active transport of H+ ions against a concentration gradient.

Proteins: H⁺/K⁺-ATPase alpha subunit;  H⁺/K⁺-ATPase beta subunit

Complex Function: This protein complex functions as a gastric H+/K+-ATPase (proton pump) that catalyzes the hydrolysis of ATP coupled with the exchange of H+ and K+ ions across the plasma membrane. It is responsible for gastric acid secretion by parietal cells in the stomach;  generating and maintaining the low pH environment necessary for food digestion and absorption. The complex is the primary target for proton pump inhibitor drugs used to treat peptic ulcers and acid reflux diseases.
Proteins: Potassium-transporting ATPase alpha chain 1 (H+/K+-ATPase α subunit); Potassium-transporting ATPase subunit beta (H+/K+-ATPase β subunit)

Complex Name: Cytochrome bc1 Complex (Complex III;  Ubiquinol-cytochrome c reductase)
Other Organisms: Human;  Mouse;  C. elegans;  Drosophila melanogaster
Complex Function: The cytochrome bc1 complex is a crucial component of the mitochondrial respiratory chain;  catalyzing electron transfer from ubiquinol to cytochrome c coupled with proton translocation across the inner mitochondrial membrane. This process contributes to the generation of a proton gradient;  which drives ATP synthesis via ATP synthase. The complex operates through the Q-cycle mechanism;  where electrons from ubiquinol are bifurcated - some transfer to cytochrome c via the Rieske iron-sulfur protein and cytochrome c1;  while others recycle through the b-type cytochromes.
Proteins: In S. cerevisiae;  the cytochrome bc1 complex consists of 10 subunits:; Cytochrome b - Core catalytic subunit; Cytochrome c1 - Core catalytic subunit; Rieske iron-sulfur protein - Core catalytic subunit; Core protein 1 (MPP alpha) - Mitochondrial processing peptidase activity; Core protein 2 (MPP beta) - Mitochondrial processing peptidase activity; Subunit 6 - Assembly factor; Subunit 7 - Stability factor; Subunit 8 - Assembly factor; Subunit 9 - Stability factor; Subunit 10 - Involved in complex assembly
Genes: COB (Cytochrome b) - Mitochondrially encoded; CYT1 (Cytochrome c1); RIP1 (Rieske iron-sulfur protein); COR1 (Core protein 1); QCR2 (Core protein 2); QCR6 (Subunit 6); QCR7 (Subunit 7); QCR8 (Subunit 8); QCR9 (Subunit 9); QCR10 (Subunit 10)

Other Organisms: Human;  Mouse;  C. elegans;  Drosophila melanogaster
Complex Function: The cytochrome bc₁ complex functions as an essential component of the mitochondrial respiratory chain;  catalyzing electron transfer from ubiquinol to cytochrome c coupled with proton translocation across the inner mitochondrial membrane. This contributes to the electrochemical proton gradient used for ATP synthesis.

Complex Function: The cytochrome bc1 complex is a central component of the mitochondrial respiratory chain. It catalyzes the transfer of electrons from ubiquinol to cytochrome c;  coupled with the translocation of protons across the inner mitochondrial membrane. This process contributes to the generation of a proton gradient that drives ATP synthesis. It employs the Q-cycle mechanism;  which involves the oxidation of ubiquinol at the Qo site and reduction of ubiquinone at the Qi site.
Proteins: Cytochrome b; Cytochrome c1; Rieske iron-sulfur protein; Core protein 1; Core protein 2; Subunit 6; Subunit 7; Subunit 8; Subunit 9; Subunit 10

Other Organisms: Human;  Mouse;  C. elegans;  Drosophila melanogaster
Complex Function: The Synaptonemal Complex is a protein structure that forms between homologous chromosomes during meiotic prophase I. In S. cerevisiae (budding yeast);  the SC facilitates crossing over between homologous chromosomes;  ensures proper chromosome segregation;  and maintains genomic integrity during meiosis. It serves as a scaffold for recombination machinery;  promotes DSB (Double-Strand Break) repair via the homologous recombination pathway;  and mediates synapsis between homologous chromosomes.
Proteins: Zip1 (central element); Zip2 (initiation complex component); Zip3 (E3 ligase;  initiation complex component); Zip4 (initiation complex component); Ecm11 (central element component); Gmc2 (central element component); Red1 (lateral element component); Hop1 (lateral element component); Spo76/Pds5 (cohesion-associated)
Genes: ZIP1; ZIP2; ZIP3; ZIP4; ECM11; GMC2; RED1; HOP1; PDS5

Other Organisms: Human;  Mouse;  C. elegans;  Drosophila melanogaster
Complex Function: The synaptonemal complex is a meiosis-specific protein structure that forms between homologous chromosomes during prophase I of meiosis. It facilitates chromosome pairing;  synapsis;  and genetic recombination between homologous chromosomes;  ensuring proper chromosome segregation and genetic diversity.
Proteins: Zip1 (central element);  Hop1 (lateral element);  Red1 (lateral element);  Zip2;  Zip3;  Zip4;  Spo16;  Ecm11
Genes: ZIP1;  HOP1;  RED1;  ZIP2;  ZIP3;  ZIP4;  SPO16;  ECM11

Other Organisms: Human;  C. elegans;  Drosophila melanogaster;  Saccharomyces cerevisiae
Complex Function: The synaptonemal complex is a proteinaceous scaffold that assembles between homologous chromosomes during meiotic prophase I. It mediates chromosome synapsis;  facilitates homologous recombination;  ensures proper crossover formation;  and promotes accurate chromosome segregation during meiosis. The SC plays a critical role in maintaining genome integrity during sexual reproduction.
Proteins: SYCP1 (Synaptonemal complex protein 1); SYCP2 (Synaptonemal complex protein 2); SYCP3 (Synaptonemal complex protein 3); SYCE1 (Synaptonemal complex central element protein 1); SYCE2 (Synaptonemal complex central element protein 2); SYCE3 (Synaptonemal complex central element protein 3); TEX12 (Testis-expressed protein 12)
Genes: Sycp1; Sycp2; Sycp3; Syce1; Syce2; Syce3; Tex12

Complex Function: This complex is involved in G protein-coupled receptor (GPCR) signaling;  where GPR55 acts as a cannabinoid receptor that;  upon activation;  couples to G12 (GNA12) to stimulate RhoA signaling. RGS2 functions as a negative regulator by accelerating the GTPase activity of GNA12;  thus terminating the signal. This complex mediates cellular responses including cytoskeletal reorganization;  cell migration;  and modulation of inflammatory processes. GPR55-GNA12 signaling has been implicated in cancer cell proliferation and metastasis;  particularly in certain cancers where this signaling axis is upregulated.
Proteins: GNA12 (Guanine nucleotide-binding protein subunit alpha-12); GPR55 (G-protein coupled receptor 55); RGS2 (Regulator of G-protein signaling 2)
Genes: GNA12 (gene ID: 2768); GPR55 (gene ID: 9290); RGS2 (gene ID: 5997)

Complex Function: This complex mediates G protein-coupled receptor signaling;  where GPR55 functions as a cannabinoid receptor;  GNA12 acts as a G-protein alpha subunit that transduces signals;  and RGS2 serves as a regulator of G-protein signaling by accelerating the inactivation of G proteins. Together;  they regulate cellular processes including cytoskeletal reorganization;  cell migration;  and various stress responses.
Proteins: Guanine nucleotide-binding protein subunit alpha-12;  G-protein coupled receptor 55;  Regulator of G-protein signaling 2

Complex Function: This complex is involved in G protein-coupled receptor (GPCR) signaling;  where GPR55 functions as a cannabinoid receptor;  GNA12 (Gα12) serves as the G-protein alpha subunit that transduces signals;  and RGS2 acts as a regulator of G-protein signaling that modulates the GTPase activity of GNA12. The complex regulates multiple cellular processes including cell migration;  cytoskeletal reorganization;  and inflammatory responses. GPR55 activation by cannabinoids and lysophosphatidylinositol leads to GNA12-mediated signaling;  which is fine-tuned by RGS2.
Proteins: Guanine nucleotide-binding protein subunit alpha-12 (GNA12); G-protein coupled receptor 55 (GPR55); Regulator of G-protein signaling 2 (RGS2)

Complex Function: MC3R is a G protein-coupled receptor that binds melanocortin peptides;  particularly γ-MSH (gamma-melanocyte stimulating hormone). In humans;  MC3R plays key roles in energy homeostasis;  inflammation regulation;  and cardiovascular function. It mediates anti-inflammatory effects through inhibition of NF-κB signaling pathways and modulates feeding behavior and metabolism. MC3R primarily signals through Gαs proteins;  activating adenylyl cyclase and elevating intracellular cAMP levels. Unlike other melanocortin receptors;  MC3R has a distinct role in regulating energy partitioning rather than directly affecting total body weight.
Proteins: MC3R functions primarily as a monomeric receptor;  though it can form homodimers. When activated;  it associates with G proteins;  typically containing:
Genes: MC3R (melanocortin 3 receptor); GNAS (G protein subunit alpha s); Various G protein beta and gamma subunit genes (GNB1-5;  GNG1-13)

Complex Function: Melanocortin receptor 3 (MC3R) is a G protein-coupled receptor that plays an important role in energy homeostasis;  particularly in the regulation of energy input and expenditure. It mediates signals from melanocortin peptides such as α-MSH;  β-MSH;  γ-MSH;  and ACTH. The activation of MC3R leads to stimulation of adenylyl cyclase;  increased cAMP production;  and subsequent activation of various downstream signaling pathways. MC3R is involved in the central control of energy balance;  metabolic homeostasis;  and inflammation. Unlike MC4R;  which primarily affects food intake;  MC3R appears to be more involved in nutrient partitioning and the regulation of energy efficiency.
Proteins: Melanocortin receptor 3

Complex Function: Melanocortin receptor 3 (MC3R) is a G protein-coupled receptor that binds melanocortin peptides including α-MSH;  β-MSH;  γ-MSH;  and ACTH. It plays a critical role in energy homeostasis;  particularly in the regulation of energy intake and expenditure. MC3R regulates feeding behavior;  metabolism;  and is involved in the central control of inflammatory responses. It functions in the hypothalamus to modulate food intake and energy balance;  with distinct roles from the related MC4R.
Proteins: Melanocortin receptor 3

Complex Function: The ATP1A1-TSHR complex facilitates the interaction between the sodium-potassium ATPase alpha-1 subunit (ATP1A1) and the thyroid-stimulating hormone receptor (TSHR). This complex is involved in thyroid hormone signaling and regulation of thyroid function. ATP1A1 functions as a non-canonical receptor for thyroid-stimulating hormone (TSH);  and when complexed with TSHR;  it contributes to the modulation of intracellular signaling cascades that regulate thyroid hormone production and secretion. The complex also plays a role in maintaining sodium and potassium ion gradients across cell membranes while participating in thyroid-specific signal transduction.
Proteins: Sodium/potassium-transporting ATPase subunit alpha-1 (ATP1A1); Thyrotropin receptor (TSHR)

Complex Function: This complex forms when the sodium-potassium ATPase (Na⁺/K⁺-ATPase) alpha-1 subunit (ATP1A1) interacts with the thyroid-stimulating hormone receptor (TSHR). This interaction mediates non-canonical signaling pathways independent of G protein coupling. The complex participates in thyroid hormone-responsive signaling cascades and may regulate cell growth;  differentiation;  and metabolism in thyroid tissue.
Proteins: Sodium/potassium-transporting ATPase subunit alpha-1;  Thyrotropin receptor

Complex Function: This complex represents a functional interaction between the sodium-potassium ATPase (specifically the alpha-1 subunit) and the thyroid-stimulating hormone receptor. The interaction modulates thyroid hormone signaling and influences sodium-potassium transport across cell membranes in thyroid tissue. The complex plays a critical role in thyroid cell function by coordinating hormone receptor signaling with membrane ion homeostasis.
Proteins: Sodium/potassium-transporting ATPase subunit alpha-1;  Thyrotropin receptor

Complex Function: The ADRA1B-CXCR4 heterodimeric complex functions in cross-talk between adrenergic and chemokine signaling pathways in humans. This complex forms when alpha-1B adrenergic receptor (ADRA1B) heterodimerizes with the chemokine receptor CXCR4. The formation of this complex modulates calcium signaling;  receptor trafficking;  and cellular responses to both adrenergic stimuli and CXCL12 (the ligand for CXCR4). This interaction has implications for vascular smooth muscle function;  immune cell migration;  and potentially cancer cell metastasis.
Proteins: Alpha-1B adrenergic receptor (ADRA1B); C-X-C chemokine receptor type 4 (CXCR4)

Complex Function: This complex forms through heteromerization of alpha-1B adrenergic receptor (ADRA1B) and C-X-C chemokine receptor type 4 (CXCR4). The complex modulates cellular signaling pathways with enhanced calcium mobilization and altered G protein coupling compared to individual receptors. It plays roles in chemotaxis;  cell migration;  and vascular smooth muscle regulation.
Proteins: Alpha-1B adrenergic receptor;  C-X-C chemokine receptor type 4

Complex Function: This heterodimeric complex formed between the alpha-1B adrenergic receptor (ADRA1B) and C-X-C chemokine receptor type 4 (CXCR4) is involved in modulating calcium signaling;  receptor trafficking;  and cellular responses to adrenergic and chemokine stimulation. The interaction between these G protein-coupled receptors (GPCRs) appears to enhance CXCR4-mediated chemotaxis and alter signaling pathways compared to the individual receptors acting alone.
Proteins: Alpha-1B adrenergic receptor;  C-X-C chemokine receptor type 4

Complex Name: Bradykinin B2 receptor-Thromboxane A2 receptor complex (Bdkrb2-Tbxa2r complex)
Complex Function: The Bdkrb2-Tbxa2r complex functions as a heterodimeric G protein-coupled receptor complex that integrates signaling between the bradykinin and thromboxane pathways in vascular smooth muscle cells. This complex mediates enhanced calcium signaling compared to the individual receptors alone;  contributing to vascular tone regulation;  inflammatory responses;  and pain perception. The complex formation allows for cross-talk between bradykinin and thromboxane A2 signaling pathways;  potentially increasing sensitivity to both ligands and modulating downstream effects on blood pressure;  and nociception.
Proteins: Bradykinin receptor B2 (Bdkrb2); Thromboxane A2 receptor (Tbxa2r)

Complex Function: This complex involves the heterodimeric interaction between bradykinin receptor B2 (Bdkrb2) and thromboxane A2 receptor (Tbxa2r);  functioning primarily in vascular smooth muscle cell signaling. The complex modulates vasoconstriction;  platelet aggregation;  and inflammatory responses through enhanced G-protein signaling. The physical interaction between these receptors amplifies downstream signaling cascades;  particularly those involved in calcium mobilization and MAP kinase activation in response to their respective ligands.
Proteins: Bradykinin receptor B2;  Thromboxane A2 receptor

Complex Function: This complex consists of the bradykinin B2 receptor (Bdkrb2) and thromboxane A2 receptor (Tbxa2r);  which functionally interact to regulate vascular smooth muscle contraction;  platelet aggregation;  and inflammatory responses. The heterodimeric complex enhances signaling sensitivity to both bradykinin and thromboxane A2;  leading to amplified calcium mobilization and enhanced vasoconstriction compared to the individual receptors.
Proteins: Bradykinin receptor B2 (Bdkrb2); Thromboxane A2 receptor (Tbxa2r)

Complex Function: The Drd3-Ednrb complex plays a role in the development of melanocytes and enteric neurons. It is involved in neural crest cell migration and development;  particularly in the colon. The interaction between these two G protein-coupled receptors appears to modulate dopaminergic and endothelin signaling;  affecting neural crest-derived cell lineages. This complex has been implicated in Hirschsprung's disease pathophysiology and intestinal aganglionosis.
Proteins: Dopamine D3 receptor (DRD3); Endothelin receptor type B (EDNRB)

Complex Function: This protein complex appears to be involved in the interaction between dopamine D3 receptor and endothelin receptor type B signaling pathways in the central nervous system. The complex may play a role in modulating neuronal signaling;  particularly in regions with co-expression of both receptors such as the striatum. The interaction potentially influences dopaminergic transmission and vascular function in specific brain regions.
Proteins: Dopamine D3 receptor;  Endothelin receptor type B

Complex Function: This protein complex involves the interaction between dopamine receptor D3 and endothelin receptor type B;  which plays a role in modulating neurotransmission and vasomotor function. The complex participates in the cross-talk between dopaminergic and endothelin signaling pathways;  particularly in neural tissues including midbrain dopaminergic neurons;  where it influences neuronal development;  synaptic plasticity;  and potentially contributes to neuroprotection mechanisms.
Proteins: Dopamine receptor D3;  Endothelin receptor type B

Complex Function: The Egflam-Gpr179 complex plays a critical role in retinal signal transmission;  specifically in maintaining the structure of the synaptic cleft at the dendrites of ON-bipolar cells. Egflam (also known as Pikachurin) is an extracellular matrix protein that binds to α-dystroglycan and is crucial for the apposition of bipolar cell dendritic tips to photoreceptor ribbon synapses. Gpr179 is a G-protein coupled receptor that recruits the RGS7-Gβ5 complex to the dendritic tips of ON-bipolar cells and is essential for depolarizing bipolar cell function. Together;  they form a complex at the photoreceptor-bipolar cell synapse that is critical for proper visual signal processing and transmission.
Proteins: Egflam (Eyes shut homolog/Pikachurin) - extracellular matrix protein; Gpr179 (G protein-coupled receptor 179) - orphan G protein-coupled receptor

Complex Function: This complex is critical for the proper function of retinal bipolar cells in the visual signal transduction pathway. It mediates the localization of mGluR6 receptors to the dendritic tips of ON-bipolar cells at the photoreceptor-to-bipolar cell synapse. The complex is essential for transmitting visual signals from photoreceptors to ON-bipolar cells;  and mutations in its components cause congenital stationary night blindness.
Proteins: Eyes shut homolog (Egflam/Pikachurin);  G-protein coupled receptor 179 (GPR179)

Complex Function: This complex functions in the retina as a critical scaffold in the synaptic cleft between bipolar cells and photoreceptors. It plays an essential role in the assembly of the transduction machinery at the dendritic tips of ON-bipolar cells;  specifically at the site where the metabotropic glutamate receptor mGluR6 is localized. The complex anchors the G-protein coupled receptor GPR179 to the extracellular matrix;  which in turn is required for proper localization of RGS proteins that regulate the mGluR6 signaling cascade. Disruption of this complex leads to congenital stationary night blindness (CSNB) due to defective synaptic transmission from photoreceptors to ON-bipolar cells.
Proteins: EGF-like;  fibronectin type III and laminin G domains protein (Pikachurin); G-protein coupled receptor 179 (GPR179)

Other Organisms: Human (although the specific 4L isoform interaction with TLR4 and SYK has been most extensively characterized in murine models)
Complex Function: The Ceacam1-4L-Syk-Tlr4 complex functions as a regulatory signaling assembly in the immune system. It serves as a critical negative regulator of TLR4-mediated inflammatory responses;  particularly in bacterial infections. When CEACAM1-4L interacts with TLR4;  it recruits SYK kinase;  leading to inhibition of MyD88-dependent NF-κB activation. This complex plays an essential role in preventing excessive inflammatory responses to pathogens;  especially gram-negative bacteria;  and helps maintain immune homeostasis in mucosal tissues.
Proteins: CEACAM1-4L (Carcinoembryonic antigen-related cell adhesion molecule 1;  4 long isoform); SYK (Spleen tyrosine kinase); TLR4 (Toll-like receptor 4)
Genes: Ceacam1 (encodes CEACAM1-4L through alternative splicing); Syk; Tlr4

Complex Function: This complex plays a pivotal role in negative regulation of Toll-like receptor 4 (TLR4) signaling in response to lipopolysaccharide (LPS) from gram-negative bacteria. When CEACAM1-4L binds to TLR4;  it recruits Syk kinase;  which phosphorylates the intracellular domain of TLR4;  thereby inhibiting downstream inflammatory signaling pathways and preventing excessive inflammatory responses.
Proteins: Carcinoembryonic antigen-related cell adhesion molecule 1;  isoform 4L (CEACAM1-4L); Spleen tyrosine kinase (Syk); Toll-like receptor 4 (TLR4)

Complex Function: This complex forms during innate immune signaling to regulate inflammatory responses. It functions as a negative regulator of Toll-like receptor 4 (TLR4) signaling by inhibiting the lipopolysaccharide (LPS)-induced inflammatory cascade. When CEACAM1-4L binds to TLR4;  it recruits SYK (spleen tyrosine kinase);  which promotes the inhibitory effects on inflammatory cytokine production;  helping to prevent excessive inflammation and endotoxic shock.
Proteins: Carcinoembryonic antigen-related cell adhesion molecule 1 (isoform 4L);  Spleen tyrosine kinase;  Toll-like receptor 4

Complex Function: This complex forms a receptor-coreceptor-ligand signaling platform essential for vascular endothelial cell migration;  proliferation;  survival;  and angiogenesis. The interaction between KDR (VEGFR2);  NRP1 (neuropilin-1);  and VEGF165 enhances VEGF signaling by increasing binding affinity and receptor activation. This complex mediates downstream signaling cascades that regulate physiological and pathological angiogenesis;  vascular permeability;  and vessel maturation.
Proteins: KDR (Kinase insert domain receptor) - A receptor tyrosine kinase that serves as the primary receptor for VEGF-A; NRP1 (Neuropilin-1) - A non-tyrosine kinase transmembrane protein that functions as a co-receptor; VEGF165 (Vascular endothelial growth factor A;  165 amino acid isoform) - A dimeric glycoprotein growth factor
Genes: KDR - Located on chromosome 4q12; NRP1 - Located on chromosome 10p11.22; VEGFA - Located on chromosome 6p21.1 (produces multiple isoforms including VEGF165)

Complex Function: This complex forms a signaling receptor assembly that mediates vascular endothelial growth factor (VEGF) signaling. It plays a critical role in angiogenesis (formation of new blood vessels);  vascular permeability;  and endothelial cell survival;  proliferation;  and migration. The complex formation enhances VEGF165 binding to KDR/VEGFR2;  potentiating downstream signal transduction pathways that regulate vascular development and maintenance.
Proteins: Vascular endothelial growth factor receptor 2 (KDR/VEGFR2); Neuropilin-1 (NRP1); Vascular endothelial growth factor A isoform 165 (VEGF165)
Genes: KDR (kinase insert domain receptor); NRP1 (neuropilin 1); VEGFA (vascular endothelial growth factor A)

Complex Function: This complex mediates vascular endothelial growth factor (VEGF) signaling;  regulating angiogenesis;  vascular permeability;  and endothelial cell migration;  proliferation;  and survival. The complex formation enhances VEGF165 binding to KDR (VEGFR2);  increasing receptor phosphorylation and downstream signaling;  which is critical for both physiological and pathological blood vessel formation.
Proteins: Vascular endothelial growth factor receptor 2 (KDR/VEGFR2); Neuropilin-1 (NRP1); Vascular endothelial growth factor A isoform 165 (VEGF165)

Complex Function: The NRP1-VEGF121 complex plays a critical role in angiogenesis (blood vessel formation) and vascular development. VEGF121 is a shorter isoform of VEGF-A that lacks heparin-binding domains but retains the ability to bind to NRP1. This complex formation facilitates signaling through VEGFR2 (VEGF Receptor 2);  enhancing endothelial cell migration;  proliferation;  and vascular permeability. The NRP1-VEGF121 interaction is particularly important during embryonic development and in pathological conditions such as tumor angiogenesis;  where it contributes to vessel formation and tumor growth.
Proteins: Neuropilin-1 (NRP1): A transmembrane glycoprotein that acts as a co-receptor for VEGF; Vascular Endothelial Growth Factor A;  isoform 121 (VEGF121): A shorter splice variant of VEGF-A that lacks heparin-binding domains
Genes: NRP1 (for Neuropilin-1); VEGFA (for VEGF121;  which is a splice variant of the VEGFA gene)

Complex Function: The NRP1-VEGF121 complex plays a crucial role in mediating angiogenesis and vascular development. When VEGF121 (a soluble isoform of vascular endothelial growth factor A) binds to neuropilin-1 (NRP1);  it enhances VEGFR2 signaling and promotes endothelial cell migration;  proliferation;  and vascular permeability. This complex is particularly important during embryonic development and in pathological conditions such as tumor angiogenesis and metastasis.
Proteins: Neuropilin-1 (NRP1);  Vascular endothelial growth factor A (isoform 121) (VEGF121)

Complex Function: This complex plays a critical role in angiogenesis and vascular development. NRP1 serves as a co-receptor for VEGF121;  enhancing VEGFR2 signaling and promoting endothelial cell migration and blood vessel formation. The complex is also involved in neuronal development;  axon guidance;  and immune cell function. In tumor biology;  this complex contributes to pathological angiogenesis supporting tumor growth and metastasis.
Proteins: Neuropilin-1 (NRP1); Vascular Endothelial Growth Factor A;  isoform 121 (VEGF121)
Genes: NRP1; VEGFA (specifically producing the 121 amino acid isoform)

Complex Function: The KDR-VEGF165 complex plays a critical role in angiogenesis;  the formation of new blood vessels. When VEGF165 (a splice variant of vascular endothelial growth factor A) binds to KDR (also known as VEGFR2);  it triggers receptor dimerization and autophosphorylation;  initiating downstream signaling cascades. These pathways promote endothelial cell proliferation;  migration;  survival;  and vascular permeability. The complex is essential for both physiological angiogenesis during development and wound healing;  as well as pathological angiogenesis in diseases such as cancer and diabetic retinopathy.
Proteins: KDR (Kinase insert domain receptor;  also known as VEGFR2 or Vascular Endothelial Growth Factor Receptor 2); VEGF165 (Vascular Endothelial Growth Factor A;  isoform 165)
Genes: KDR gene (encodes KDR/VEGFR2); VEGFA gene (encodes VEGF165 through alternative splicing)

Complex Function: This protein complex mediates vascular endothelial cell proliferation;  survival;  migration;  and angiogenesis. When VEGF165 (a splice variant of VEGFA) binds to KDR (VEGFR2);  it triggers receptor dimerization and autophosphorylation;  activating downstream signaling cascades that regulate blood vessel formation;  vascular permeability;  and endothelial cell function. The complex is crucial for both physiological angiogenesis during development and pathological angiogenesis in diseases such as cancer.
Proteins: Vascular endothelial growth factor receptor 2 (KDR/VEGFR2);  Vascular endothelial growth factor A (VEGFA;  specifically the 165 amino acid isoform)

Complex Function: The KDR-VEGF165 complex is critical for mediating angiogenesis;  vascular permeability;  and endothelial cell survival. When VEGF165 (a major isoform of VEGF-A) binds to KDR (also known as VEGFR-2);  it triggers receptor dimerization and autophosphorylation;  activating downstream signaling cascades that promote endothelial cell proliferation;  migration;  and tube formation. This complex plays a fundamental role in both developmental and pathological angiogenesis;  including tumor vascularization.
Proteins: Vascular endothelial growth factor receptor 2 (KDR/VEGFR-2); Vascular endothelial growth factor A (VEGF-A;  isoform VEGF165)

Complex Function: The FLT4-VEGFC complex functions primarily in lymphangiogenesis - the formation of lymphatic vessels from pre-existing lymphatic vessels. Upon binding of VEGFC to the FLT4 receptor (also known as VEGFR-3);  the receptor dimerizes and undergoes autophosphorylation;  activating downstream signaling pathways including PI3K/Akt and MAPK cascades. This signaling promotes lymphatic endothelial cell proliferation;  migration;  and survival. The complex also plays roles in embryonic cardiovascular development and pathological angiogenesis in certain diseases.
Proteins: FLT4 (Fms-related receptor tyrosine kinase 4;  also known as VEGFR-3); VEGFC (Vascular endothelial growth factor C)

Complex Function: The FLT4-VEGFC complex is primarily involved in lymphangiogenesis;  the formation of new lymphatic vessels. Upon binding of VEGFC to the FLT4 receptor (also known as VEGFR3);  the complex initiates intracellular signaling cascades that stimulate lymphatic endothelial cell proliferation;  migration;  and survival. This complex is essential for lymphatic vessel development during embryogenesis and plays a role in lymphatic vessel maintenance in adults. It also contributes to tumor lymphangiogenesis and lymphatic metastasis in various cancers.
Proteins: Vascular endothelial growth factor receptor 3 (FLT4/VEGFR3); Vascular endothelial growth factor C (VEGFC)

Complex Function: This complex mediates lymphangiogenesis and maintenance of the lymphatic endothelium. When VEGFC (Vascular Endothelial Growth Factor C) binds to FLT4 (Vascular Endothelial Growth Factor Receptor 3);  it triggers receptor dimerization and autophosphorylation;  activating downstream signaling pathways that promote lymphatic endothelial cell proliferation;  migration;  and survival. This signaling is essential for lymphatic vessel development;  lymphatic homeostasis;  and lymphatic vessel remodeling.
Proteins: Vascular endothelial growth factor receptor 3 (VEGFR-3); Vascular endothelial growth factor C

Complex Function: The ITGA3-ITGB1 complex functions as a receptor for laminin;  specifically laminin-5 (laminin-332);  collagen;  and fibronectin in the extracellular matrix. It mediates cell-matrix adhesion;  participates in cell-surface mediated signaling;  and regulates epithelial cell migration and tissue organization. In humans;  it plays critical roles in kidney development;  skin integrity;  and lung alveolar formation. The complex is particularly important for basement membrane organization;  keratinocyte migration during wound healing;  and maintaining epithelial cell polarity.
Proteins: Integrin alpha-3 (ITGA3); Integrin beta-1 (ITGB1)
Genes: ITGA3 (integrin subunit alpha 3); ITGB1 (integrin subunit beta 1)

Complex Function: The ITGA3-ITGB1 complex functions as a receptor for laminin;  collagen;  and fibronectin. It plays a crucial role in cell-matrix adhesion;  cell migration;  and tissue organization. In epithelial cells;  α3β1 integrin mediates adhesion to the basement membrane and regulates epithelial cell polarity;  differentiation;  and wound healing. The complex also participates in signaling pathways that control cell survival;  proliferation;  and cytoskeletal organization.
Proteins: Integrin alpha-3 (ITGA3);  Integrin beta-1 (ITGB1)

Complex Function: The ITGA3-ITGB1 complex functions as a receptor for fibronectin;  laminin;  collagen;  epiligrin;  thrombospondin and CSPG4. It mediates cell-cell and cell-matrix adhesion in epithelial tissues;  playing crucial roles in kidney and skin development;  wound healing;  and maintaining epithelial cell integrity. This integrin heterodimer primarily binds to laminin-5 (laminin-332) in basement membranes and is essential for proper organization of extracellular matrix.
Proteins: Integrin alpha-3 (ITGA3);  Integrin beta-1 (ITGB1)

Other Organisms: Human;  Mouse;  C. elegans;  Drosophila melanogaster
Complex Function: The GARP complex functions as a tethering factor for retrograde vesicle trafficking from endosomes to the trans-Golgi network (TGN). It captures and facilitates the fusion of endosome-derived transport vesicles with the TGN membranes;  playing a crucial role in the recycling of proteins such as TGN46;  certain SNAREs;  and mannose-6-phosphate receptors from endosomes back to the TGN.
Proteins: Vps51 (15.5 kDa); Vps52 (43 kDa); Vps53 (96 kDa); Vps54 (100 kDa)

Other Organisms: Human;  Mouse;  Drosophila melanogaster;  C. elegans
Complex Function: The GARP complex is a tethering complex that mediates retrograde transport of proteins from endosomes to the trans-Golgi network (TGN). It plays a critical role in maintaining proper sorting and recycling of transmembrane proteins;  particularly those involved in lysosomal enzyme trafficking. The complex captures and tethers vesicles that originate from endosomes to facilitate their fusion with the TGN membrane through interactions with SNARE proteins.
Proteins: Vps51 (Vacuolar protein sorting-associated protein 51); Vps52 (Vacuolar protein sorting-associated protein 52); Vps53 (Vacuolar protein sorting-associated protein 53); Vps54 (Vacuolar protein sorting-associated protein 54)

Complex Name: LY96-TLR4 complex (also known as MD-2/TLR4 complex)
Complex Function: The LY96-TLR4 complex serves as a crucial pattern recognition receptor in innate immunity;  primarily responsible for detecting lipopolysaccharide (LPS) from Gram-negative bacteria. Upon LPS binding;  the complex initiates signal transduction cascades that activate NF-κB and lead to the production of pro-inflammatory cytokines and type I interferons. This complex is essential for mounting immune responses against Gram-negative bacterial infections but can also contribute to septic shock when excessively activated.

Complex Function: The LY96-TLR4 complex forms the primary receptor for lipopolysaccharide (LPS);  a major component of the outer membrane of Gram-negative bacteria. This complex is essential for the innate immune system's recognition of bacterial pathogens and initiates signaling cascades leading to the production of inflammatory cytokines and type I interferons. Upon LPS binding;  the complex recruits adaptor proteins (MyD88;  TIRAP;  TRIF;  TRAM) to activate downstream pathways;  including NF-κB and IRF3;  triggering inflammatory responses crucial for host defense against bacterial infections.

LY96 (also known as MD-2) binds directly to LPS and associates with TLR4;  facilitating TLR4 dimerization upon LPS recognition. This dimerization triggers downstream signaling cascades via the MyD88-dependent and TRIF-dependent pathways;  leading to the activation of NF-κB and IRF3 transcription factors;  production of pro-inflammatory cytokines;  type I interferons;  and ultimately the mounting of inflammatory responses against gram-negative bacterial infections.

Complex Function: The RAD6-RAD18 ubiquitin ligase complex functions as the primary E2-E3 enzyme pair responsible for PCNA monoubiquitination at K164 in response to DNA damage. This ubiquitination is a key mediator of DNA damage tolerance through translesion synthesis (TLS);  allowing cells to bypass DNA lesions during replication. The complex recognizes regions of single-stranded DNA exposed at stalled replication forks and catalyzes the transfer of ubiquitin to PCNA;  which then recruits specialized TLS polymerases to bypass the damage. The complex is essential for post-replication repair and maintaining genome stability.
Proteins: Rad6 (E2 ubiquitin-conjugating enzyme); Rad18 (E3 ubiquitin ligase)

It monoubiquitinates proliferating cell nuclear antigen (PCNA) at lysine 164 in response to DNA damage;  particularly from UV radiation and chemical agents. This modification triggers DNA damage bypass mechanisms including translesion synthesis (TLS) and template switching;  allowing replication to continue past damaged DNA lesions.
Proteins: Ubiquitin-conjugating enzyme E2 2 (Rad6/Ubc2); E3 ubiquitin-protein ligase RAD18

Complex Function: This complex mediates post-replication repair by initiating DNA damage tolerance through the monoubiquitination of proliferating cell nuclear antigen (PCNA) at lysine 164. The complex is activated in response to stalled replication forks caused by DNA lesions;  enabling cells to bypass DNA damage during replication and preventing replication fork collapse. The RAD6-RAD18 complex is essential for tolerance of UV-induced DNA damage and plays a crucial role in translesion DNA synthesis (TLS) pathway activation.
Proteins: Ubiquitin-conjugating enzyme E2 2 (Rad6/Ubc2); E3 ubiquitin-protein ligase RAD18

Complex Function: The PHO85-PHO80 CDK-cyclin complex functions as a negative regulator of the phosphate responsive signaling pathway in yeast. When phosphate is abundant;  this complex phosphorylates the transcription factor PHO4;  causing its export from the nucleus and preventing the transcription of phosphate-responsive genes. Under phosphate-limiting conditions;  the complex is inhibited by PHO81;  allowing PHO4 to remain in the nucleus and activate the expression of genes involved in phosphate acquisition and metabolism;  such as acid phosphatases and phosphate transporters.

Other Organisms: Not directly conserved as the specific CED-3-CED-4-MAC-1 complex;  though functional homologs of the apoptosome exist in humans (Apaf-1/caspase-9 complex);  Drosophila (Dark/Dronc complex);  and mice.

MAC-1 (Mitochondrial ATPase Component 1) regulates this activation process by binding to CED-4;  influencing its ability to oligomerize and activate CED-3. The complex is essential for developmental cell death and functions downstream of CED-9 (anti-apoptotic) and EGL-1 (pro-apoptotic) in the canonical apoptosis pathway.

Complex Function: This complex functions in the programmed cell death (apoptosis) pathway in C. elegans. CED-3 is a caspase that executes apoptosis;  CED-4 is an adaptor protein that oligomerizes and activates CED-3;  and MAC-1 is a AAA+ ATPase that regulates the CED-3/CED-4 interaction. Together;  they form a complex that triggers the proteolytic cascade leading to cell death when apoptotic signals override survival signals.

Complex Function: The nuclear mitotic cohesin complex is primarily responsible for sister chromatid cohesion during cell division. The complex forms a ring-like structure that topologically embraces DNA.

The complex loads onto chromosomes before DNA replication and is maintained until the metaphase-anaphase transition when it is cleaved by separase.

Complex Name: Ndc80 Complex (also known as HEC1 complex in humans)
Other Organisms: Human;  Mouse;  C. elegans;  Drosophila melanogaster
Complex Function: The Ndc80 complex is a crucial component of the kinetochore;  serving as the primary microtubule-binding interface during mitosis. It establishes and maintains the connection between kinetochores and spindle microtubules;  facilitating chromosome alignment and segregation during mitosis. The complex also plays a key role in spindle assembly checkpoint signaling;  ensuring proper chromosome segregation by delaying anaphase onset until all chromosomes are properly attached to the spindle.
Proteins: Ndc80 (also known as HEC1 in humans); Nuf2; Spc24; Spc25

Other Organisms: Human;  Mouse;  C. elegans;  Drosophila melanogaster
Complex Function: The Ndc80 complex is a critical component of the kinetochore and serves as the primary microtubule-binding element at the kinetochore. It functions to establish and maintain the end-on attachment of spindle microtubules to kinetochores during mitosis and meiosis;  which is essential for proper chromosome segregation. The complex also plays a role in the spindle assembly checkpoint (SAC) signaling;  which prevents anaphase onset until all chromosomes are properly attached to the spindle.
Proteins: Ndc80 (also called Hec1 or TID3);  Nuf2;  Spc24;  Spc25

Complex Function: The Ndc80 complex is a crucial component of the kinetochore and serves as the primary microtubule-binding element at kinetochores. It forms a dumbbell-shaped heterotetramer that bridges between the inner kinetochore and the microtubules. This complex is essential for establishing and maintaining proper kinetochore-microtubule attachments during mitosis;  ensuring accurate chromosome segregation. It also participates in the spindle assembly checkpoint signaling;  which prevents anaphase onset until all chromosomes are properly attached to the mitotic spindle.
Proteins: Ndc80 (also known as Hec1 in humans);  Nuf2;  Spc24;  Spc25

It is essential for proper chromosome segregation during mitosis by establishing connections between centromeric DNA and spindle microtubules. The complex specifically provides a structural platform that bridges the chromatin-proximal components with the microtubule-binding modules of the KMN (KNL1;  Mis12;  Ndc80) network.

Complex Function: The Mis12 complex serves as a central hub in the kinetochore assembly pathway;  connecting the inner kinetochore (chromatin-proximal) components to the outer kinetochore microtubule-binding components. It plays a crucial role in chromosome segregation during mitosis by helping to establish stable attachments between chromosomes and the mitotic spindle. The complex is essential for proper kinetochore assembly;  ensuring accurate chromosome alignment and segregation during cell division.

Additionally;  the KDR-VEGF165 complex is involved in pathological conditions;  such as tumor growth and metastasis;  where it contributes to the formation of tumor vasculature.

Complex Function: The PHO85-PHO80 CDK-cyclin complex plays a crucial role in the regulation of phosphate metabolism in Saccharomyces cerevisiae. It is involved in the phosphorylation and inactivation of the transcription factor Pho4;  which is a key regulator of phosphate-responsive genes. When phosphate levels are high;  the PHO85-PHO80 complex phosphorylates Pho4;  leading to its export from the nucleus and subsequent inactivation. This results in the repression of phosphate-responsive genes. Conversely;  when phosphate levels are low;  the PHO85-PHO80 complex is inactive;  allowing Pho4 to remain in the nucleus and activate the transcription of phosphate-responsive genes.

Organism: The AMPK complex is highly conserved across eukaryotic species;  but it is most prominently studied in humans (Homo sapiens).

It acts as a central metabolic sensor;  monitoring the cellular energy status and responding to changes in the AMP/ATP ratio. When activated by increased AMP levels or other metabolic stresses;  AMPK stimulates catabolic pathways that generate ATP;  such as fatty acid oxidation and glucose uptake;  while inhibiting anabolic processes that consume ATP;  such as lipid and protein synthesis. This helps restore energy balance within the cell.

Other Organisms: Among the listed organisms (Human;  Mouse;  C. elegans;  Drosophila melanogaster;  Saccharomyces cerevisiae);  this exact complex with the specific composition (GNA12-GPR55-RGS2) is only well-characterized in humans. Mouse orthologs of the individual proteins exist;  but there is no clear evidence for the same tripartite complex or analogous function in the other species.
Complex Function: In humans;  the GNA12-GPR55-RGS2 complex is involved in G protein-coupled receptor (GPCR) signaling;  particularly modulating signaling cascades initiated by GPR55;  a putative cannabinoid receptor. GNA12 (G alpha 12) mediates signals from GPR55 to downstream effectors;  influencing cellular processes like cytoskeletal remodeling and cell migration. RGS2 (Regulator of G protein Signaling 2) serves as a GTPase-activating protein;  accelerating the termination of GNA12 signaling;  thereby regulating the intensity and duration of receptor-mediated signaling.
Proteins: GNA12 (Guanine nucleotide-binding protein subunit alpha-12); GPR55 (G protein-coupled receptor 55); RGS2 (Regulator of G-protein signaling 2)
Genes: GNA12 → GNA12 gene; GPR55 → GPR55 gene; RGS2 → RGS2 gene

Complex Function: This complex is involved in G protein-coupled signaling. GPR55 is an orphan G protein-coupled receptor that can couple to the GNA12 (Gα12) subunit;  facilitating intracellular signaling pathways (notably activation of RhoA);  while RGS2 negatively regulates this signaling through its GTPase-activating activity;  thereby modulating signal duration and intensity.
Proteins: G protein subunit alpha 12 (GNA12);  G protein-coupled receptor 55 (GPR55);  Regulator of G-protein signaling 2 (RGS2)

Complex Function: This complex is involved in G protein-coupled signal transduction;  specifically modulating cellular responses to lysophosphatidylinositol (LPI) and cannabinoids. The assembly of this complex is implicated in various cellular processes;  including proliferation;  migration;  and possibly nociception and inflammation.
Proteins: Guanine nucleotide-binding protein G(alpha)12 (GNA12);  G-protein coupled receptor 55 (GPR55);  Regulator of G-protein signaling 2 (RGS2)

The interaction may be relevant in the regulation of thyroid hormone synthesis and release.
Proteins: ATP1A1 (Na+/K+ ATPase α1 subunit); TSHR (Thyroid-stimulating hormone receptor)
Genes: ATP1A1 (gene encoding Na+/K+ ATPase α1 subunit); TSHR (gene encoding thyroid-stimulating hormone receptor)

Proteins: Sodium/potassium-transporting ATPase subunit alpha-1;  Thyroid stimulating hormone receptor

Proteins: Sodium/potassium-transporting ATPase subunit alpha-1 (ATP1A1);  Thyroid stimulating hormone receptor (TSHR)

Other Organisms: No experimental or literature-supported evidence currently exists for the formation of the ADRA1B-CXCR4 complex in Mouse (Mus musculus);  Caenorhabditis elegans;  Drosophila melanogaster;  or Saccharomyces cerevisiae.
Complex Function: The ADRA1B-CXCR4 complex is a heteromeric protein-protein interaction between two G protein-coupled receptors (GPCRs): adrenergic receptor alpha-1B (ADRA1B) and C-X-C chemokine receptor type 4 (CXCR4). In Homo sapiens;  this complex formation modulates intracellular signaling pathways;  specifically enabling CXCR4 to induce transactivation of ADRA1B-dependent Gq/11 signaling cascades;  which are otherwise typically independent of each other. This interaction influences cell migration;  proliferation;  and possibly cancer progression via altered responses to their respective ligands (noradrenaline for ADRA1B;  CXCL12/SDF-1 for CXCR4).
Proteins: Adrenergic receptor alpha-1B (ADRA1B);  C-X-C chemokine receptor type 4 (CXCR4)

Other Organisms: N/A (no validated evidence for this complex in Mouse;  C. elegans;  Drosophila melanogaster;  or Saccharomyces cerevisiae)
Complex Function: The ADRA1B-CXCR4 complex is a protein-protein interaction between the alpha-1B adrenergic receptor (ADRA1B) and the C-X-C chemokine receptor type 4 (CXCR4). In Homo sapiens;  this complex has been shown to modulate G-protein coupled receptor (GPCR) signaling;  leading to transinhibition of Gq protein signaling by the Gi-coupled receptor CXCR4 upon agonist stimulation. This crosstalk has regulatory effects on downstream cellular responses such as cell migration;  calcium signaling;  and potentially cancer cell metastasis.
Proteins: Alpha-1B adrenergic receptor (ADRA1B);  C-X-C chemokine receptor type 4 (CXCR4)

Complex Function: The ADRA1B-CXCR4 complex is a heteromeric receptor complex formed by the physical association between the alpha-1B adrenergic receptor (ADRA1B) and the C-X-C chemokine receptor type 4 (CXCR4). This complex modulates signaling pathways distinct from those regulated by either receptor alone;  including enhanced G-protein and β-arrestin mediated signaling;  and alters responses to endogenous ligands such as norepinephrine and CXCL12. The complex has been implicated in tumorigenesis;  cell migration;  and metastasis in various cancers.
Proteins: Alpha-1B adrenergic receptor (ADRA1B);  C-X-C chemokine receptor type 4 (CXCR4)

Other Organisms: Not confirmed in Mouse;  C. elegans;  Drosophila melanogaster;  or Saccharomyces cerevisiae.
Complex Function: The Bdkrb2-Tbxa2r complex is a heterodimeric association between the Bradykinin receptor B2 (Bdkrb2) and Thromboxane A2 receptor (Tbxa2r);  both of which are G protein-coupled receptors (GPCRs). In humans;  this complex modulates intracellular calcium signaling and vascular tone regulation. The interaction between these two receptors has been experimentally linked to altered vasoconstriction responses and may play a role in thrombosis and vascular inflammation;  potentially affecting cardiovascular homeostasis and disease.
Proteins: Bradykinin receptor B2 (Bdkrb2);  Thromboxane A2 receptor (Tbxa2r)

Complex Function: Presumed heteromeric G-protein coupled receptor (GPCR) complex involved in modulating vascular tone and thromboxane signaling. Evidence suggests the complex may influence vasoconstriction and inflammatory responses via functional interactions between bradykinin and thromboxane pathways.
Proteins: Bradykinin receptor B2 (Bdkrb2);  Thromboxane A2 receptor (Tbxa2r)

Complex Function: Heteromeric G protein-coupled receptor (GPCR) complex formed between Bradykinin receptor B2 (Bdkrb2) and Thromboxane A2 receptor (Tbxa2r);  implicated in modulating signal transduction pathways relevant to vascular tone;  inflammation;  and platelet aggregation. The formation of this heteromer influences ligand binding properties and downstream signaling;  contributing to the regulation of cardiovascular and inflammatory responses.
Proteins: Bradykinin receptor B2;  Thromboxane A2 receptor

Other Organisms: Not confirmed in Human;  Caenorhabditis elegans;  Drosophila melanogaster;  or Saccharomyces cerevisiae as a functional complex.
Complex Function: The Drd3-Ednrb complex involves the physical association between dopamine receptor D3 (Drd3) and endothelin receptor type B (Ednrb);  two G protein-coupled receptors (GPCRs). Experimental data in mouse nervous tissue suggest that this heteromeric complex modulates dopaminergic neurotransmission and endothelin signaling;  potentially impacting neurovascular regulation and neurotransmitter release patterns in the brain.
Proteins: Dopamine receptor D3 (Drd3);  Endothelin receptor type B (Ednrb)

Complex Function: Heteromeric complex between the dopamine receptor D3 (Drd3) and endothelin receptor type B (Ednrb);  implicated in modulating neurotransmission;  dopaminergic signaling;  and endothelin-mediated pathways in the brain;  potentially affecting neuropsychiatric function and vascular regulation. Experimental evidence suggests receptor heteromerization can modulate ligand binding and downstream signaling.
Proteins: Dopamine receptor D3;  Endothelin receptor type B

Complex Function: This complex is formed by the interaction of the Dopamine receptor D3 (DRD3) and the Endothelin receptor type B (EDNRB);  both of which are G protein-coupled receptors. The functional significance involves modulation of neurochemical signaling pathways;  primarily affecting dopaminergic and endothelin-mediated processes such as neurovascular regulation and neurotransmitter release. Direct functional characterization of this heteromeric complex has been documented in dopaminergic neuronal systems;  impacting receptor crosstalk and signaling bias.
Proteins: Dopamine receptor D3 (DRD3);  Endothelin receptor type B (EDNRB)

Complex Function: The Egflam-GPR179 complex is essential for the localization and function of G protein-coupled receptor 179 (GPR179) at the dendritic tips of ON-bipolar cells in the retina. This complex is crucial for proper synaptic transmission in the visual pathway;  specifically mediating the ON response in retinal signal transduction from photoreceptors to ON-bipolar cells. Mutations affecting this complex can lead to congenital stationary night blindness (cCSNB) due to disrupted signal relay in the retina.
Proteins: Egflam protein;  Gpr179 protein

Complex Function: The Egflam-Gpr179 complex is essential for synaptic transmission in the retinal ON bipolar cells. Egflam (also known as Pikachurin) interacts extracellularly with the orphan G protein-coupled receptor GPR179 to facilitate localization and functional organization of the post-synaptic signaling machinery required for visual signal transduction. Loss or disruption of this complex results in abnormal visual signaling;  as observed in congenital stationary night blindness.
Proteins: Pikachurin (Egflam);  G protein-coupled receptor 179 (Gpr179)

Complex Function: The Egflam-Gpr179 complex is an extracellular synaptic organizer critical for the proper functioning of the metabotropic glutamate receptor 6 (mGluR6) pathway in retinal ON bipolar cells. Egflam (also known as Pikachurin) mediates the trans-synaptic alignment and stabilization of GPR179 at the dendritic tips of ON bipolar cells;  which is essential for photoreceptor-to-bipolar cell signal transmission and vision.
Proteins: Egflam (Pikachurin);  Gpr179

Other Organisms: There is no robust evidence for the existence of this exact complex in Human;  C. elegans;  Drosophila melanogaster;  or Saccharomyces cerevisiae;  though orthologous proteins exist in Human;  but not the same characterized complex.
Complex Function: This complex is believed to mediate innate immune signaling;  with CEACAM1 (specifically its long cytoplasmic isoform 4L) acting as a co-receptor that interacts with TLR4 (Toll-like receptor 4) to modulate LPS (lipopolysaccharide) response in leukocytes. SYK (spleen tyrosine kinase) bridges signaling between CEACAM1 and TLR4;  resulting in the activation or suppression of inflammatory pathways;  particularly influencing cytokine production and immune cell activation.
Proteins: CEACAM1-4L (Carcinoembryonic antigen-related cell adhesion molecule 1;  4L isoform); SYK (Spleen tyrosine kinase); TLR4 (Toll-like receptor 4)
Genes: Ceacam1 (for CEACAM1-4L); Syk (for SYK); Tlr4 (for TLR4)

Complex Function: This complex is involved in the regulation of immune cell activation. Specifically;  CEACAM1-4L (Carcinoembryonic Antigen-Related Cell Adhesion Molecule 1;  isoform 4L) interacts with Syk (Spleen tyrosine kinase) and TLR4 (Toll-like receptor 4) to modulate signaling events in myeloid and endothelial cells;  orchestrating responses to pathogens and regulating inflammation in the mouse immune system.
Proteins: CEACAM1-4L;  Syk;  Tlr4

Complex Function: Acts as an immunoregulatory complex that integrates cell adhesion signaling (via Ceacam1);  immune receptor tyrosine kinase signaling (via Syk);  and pathogen-associated molecular pattern recognition (via Tlr4) to modulate inflammatory and immune cell responses;  especially in myeloid and epithelial cells.
Proteins: Carcinoembryonic antigen-related cell adhesion molecule 1 long isoform (Ceacam1-4L);  Spleen tyrosine kinase (Syk);  Toll-like receptor 4 (Tlr4)

Other Organisms: Mouse (homologous Kdr-Nrp1-Vegfa165 complex exists;  but functional and expression differences exist;  NOT found in C. elegans;  Drosophila melanogaster;  Saccharomyces cerevisiae)
Complex Function: Mediates high-affinity binding and cellular signaling in response to vascular endothelial growth factor (VEGF)-A165. This complex facilitates VEGF165-induced angiogenic signaling;  endothelial cell migration;  and new blood vessel formation via cooperative interaction of the VEGF165 ligand (VEGFA);  its primary receptor (KDR/VEGFR2);  and co-receptor NRP1 (Neuropilin-1);  optimizing downstream endothelial VEGFR2 signaling.
Proteins: Kinase insert domain receptor (KDR/VEGFR2); Neuropilin-1 (NRP1); Vascular endothelial growth factor A;  isoform 165 (VEGFA165)
Genes: KDR (for VEGFR2); NRP1 (for Neuropilin-1); VEGFA (for VEGFA165 peptide)

Complex Function: This trimeric complex mediates the binding of the vascular endothelial growth factor A isoform 165 (VEGF165) to its principal receptor kinase (KDR/VEGFR2) and the coreceptor neuropilin-1 (NRP1);  which collectively initiates potent angiogenic signaling essential for physiological and pathological blood vessel formation.
Proteins: Vascular endothelial growth factor receptor 2 (VEGFR2/KDR);  Neuropilin-1 (NRP1);  Vascular endothelial growth factor A isoform 165 (VEGFA-165)

Complex Function: This complex is involved in the high-affinity binding and signaling of Vascular Endothelial Growth Factor A165 (VEGF165);  a key mediator of angiogenesis. The complex forms when VEGF165 bridges the receptor tyrosine kinase KDR (also known as VEGFR2) and the co-receptor Neuropilin-1 (NRP1);  resulting in enhanced signaling required for endothelial cell proliferation;  migration;  and vascular development.
Proteins: Vascular endothelial growth factor receptor 2 (KDR/VEGFR2);  Neuropilin-1 (NRP1);  and Vascular endothelial growth factor A165 (VEGFA165)

Other Organisms: None (of Mouse;  C. elegans;  Drosophila melanogaster;  or Saccharomyces cerevisiae;  only Human expresses the physiologically relevant NRP1-VEGF121 complex;  while mouse expresses both paralogs;  the specific human NRP1 + VEGF121 isoform complex is primarily characterized in Human.)
Complex Function: Mediates interaction between neuropilin-1 (NRP1) and the vascular endothelial growth factor 121 isoform (VEGF121);  facilitating VEGF-induced angiogenic signaling;  vascular permeability;  and endothelial cell migration in human vasculature.
Proteins: Neuropilin-1 (NRP1);  Vascular Endothelial Growth Factor 121 (VEGF121)
Genes: NRP1 (neuropilin-1);  VEGFA (vascular endothelial growth factor A;  isoform 121)

Complex Function: Mediates the binding of Vascular Endothelial Growth Factor 121 (VEGF121) to Neuropilin-1 (NRP1);  facilitating VEGF-induced angiogenesis through enhancement of VEGF signaling via its primary receptor (VEGFR2) on endothelial cells. This complex is critical for vascular development and modulation of endothelial cell function.
Proteins: Neuropilin-1;  Vascular endothelial growth factor A (VEGF121 isoform)

Complex Function: Receptor-ligand complex in which Vascular Endothelial Growth Factor 121 (VEGF121) binds Neuropilin-1 (NRP1);  facilitating angiogenesis by enhancing VEGF receptor signaling and endothelial cell migration.
Proteins: Neuropilin-1;  Vascular Endothelial Growth Factor 121 isoform (proteolytically processed VEGFA isoform)

Other Organisms: Mouse (orthologs are present;  complex is functional in mouse);  not reported in C. elegans;  Drosophila melanogaster;  or Saccharomyces cerevisiae.
Complex Function: Mediates angiogenic signaling by binding the vascular endothelial growth factor VEGF165 isoform to the high-affinity receptor KDR (also known as VEGFR2);  promoting endothelial cell proliferation;  migration;  survival;  and vascular permeability;  central to vascular development;  tumor angiogenesis;  and wound healing.
Proteins: KDR/VEGFR2 (Vascular endothelial growth factor receptor 2);  VEGFA165 (Vascular endothelial growth factor A;  165 amino acid isoform)

Complex Function: High-affinity receptor-ligand complex that initiates endothelial cell proliferation;  migration;  and new blood vessel formation (angiogenesis) in response to VEGF-A165 binding. Key player in physiological and pathological angiogenesis.
Proteins: Vascular endothelial growth factor receptor 2 (KDR/Flk-1);  Vascular endothelial growth factor A isoform 165 (VEGF-A165)

Complex Function: KDR-VEGF165 is a ligand-receptor signaling complex essential for angiogenesis;  it mediates vascular endothelial cell proliferation;  migration;  and survival in response to vascular endothelial growth factor (VEGF) stimulation.
Proteins: Vascular endothelial growth factor receptor 2 (KDR;  also known as VEGFR2);  Vascular endothelial growth factor A isoform 165 (VEGF165)

Other Organisms: Mouse (mus musculus;  orthologous complex is present and functionally conserved).
Complex Function: The FLT4-VEGFC complex mediates lymphangiogenesis and vascular development in human physiology. It is formed by the binding of the vascular endothelial growth factor C (VEGFC) ligand to its receptor FLT4 (also known as VEGFR-3);  primarily on the surface of lymphatic endothelial cells;  activating downstream signaling essential for the proliferation;  migration;  and survival of lymphatic endothelial cells.
Proteins: FLT4 (VEGFR-3);  VEGFC

Complex Function: This is a receptor-ligand complex where VEGFC (Vascular Endothelial Growth Factor C) binds to the FLT4 (also known as VEGFR3;  Fms-related tyrosine kinase 4) receptor. The primary function is the regulation of lymphangiogenesis and;  to a lesser extent;  angiogenesis;  by promoting proliferation;  migration;  and survival of lymphatic endothelial cells.
Proteins: Vascular endothelial growth factor C (VEGFC);  Vascular endothelial growth factor receptor 3 (VEGFR-3/FLT4)

Complex Function: This is a receptor-ligand signaling complex involved in lymphangiogenesis. FLT4 (also known as VEGFR-3) is the endothelial receptor tyrosine kinase for the VEGFC ligand. Upon VEGFC binding;  FLT4 undergoes dimerization and autophosphorylation;  activating downstream signaling cascades that drive the development and maintenance of the lymphatic vasculature.
Proteins: Vascular endothelial growth factor receptor 3 (VEGFR-3;  FLT4);  Vascular endothelial growth factor C (VEGFC)

Other Organisms: The specific ITGA3 (Integrin alpha-3) and ITGB1 (Integrin beta-1) pairing is also present in mouse;  but not in C. elegans;  Drosophila melanogaster;  or Saccharomyces cerevisiae.
Complex Function: The ITGA3-ITGB1 complex;  also known as the integrin α3β1 complex;  primarily mediates cell-extracellular matrix (ECM) adhesion. In humans;  it is especially important for cellular interactions with laminin in the basement membrane;  contributing to cell migration;  tissue morphogenesis;  wound healing;  and maintenance of epithelial tissue architecture. It plays a crucial role in kidney development;  skin integrity;  and tumor cell migration/metastasis.
Proteins: Integrin alpha-3 (ITGA3);  Integrin beta-1 (ITGB1)

Complex Function: Heterodimeric cell surface receptor mediating cell-matrix adhesion;  with a prominent role in laminin binding;  cell migration;  signal transduction;  and regulation of cell morphology and proliferation;  crucial for epithelial integrity;  development;  and organogenesis in human tissues.
Proteins: Integrin alpha-3;  Integrin beta-1

Complex Function: The ITGA3-ITGB1 complex forms the α3β1 integrin;  a transmembrane adhesion receptor primarily responsible for mediating cell-extracellular matrix adhesion;  especially to laminins and certain collagens. In humans;  it is crucial for epithelial cell adhesion;  migration;  signal transduction;  maintenance of basement membrane integrity;  and tissue morphogenesis. It also regulates interactions in development;  wound healing;  and cancer metastasis.
Proteins: Integrin alpha-3 (ITGA3);  Integrin beta-1 (ITGB1)

Other Organisms: Mus musculus (Mouse);  Drosophila melanogaster;  Saccharomyces cerevisiae;  and Caenorhabditis elegans
Complex Function: The Golgi-associated retrograde protein (GARP) complex is a multisubunit tethering complex essential for retrograde transport of vesicles from endosomes to the trans-Golgi network. GARP is required for maintaining Golgi integrity and proper sorting of proteins;  especially in vesicle fusion events mediated by SNARE complex assembly.
Proteins: VPS51 (also known as Ang2);  VPS52;  VPS53;  VPS54
Genes: VPS51 (Gene: VPS51);  VPS52 (Gene: VPS52);  VPS53 (Gene: VPS53);  VPS54 (Gene: VPS54)

Other Organisms: Human;  Mouse;  Drosophila melanogaster;  C. elegans
Complex Function: The Golgi-associated retrograde protein (GARP) complex is essential for tethering and fusion of retrograde transport vesicles from endosomes to the trans-Golgi network;  thereby maintaining Golgi integrity and proper protein sorting.
Proteins: Vps51p;  Vps52p;  Vps53p;  Vps54p

Other Organisms: Human;  Mouse;  Drosophila melanogaster;  C. elegans
Complex Function: The Golgi-associated retrograde protein (GARP) complex is a tethering factor required for the fusion of endosome-derived transport vesicles with the trans-Golgi network. It functions in retrograde vesicle-mediated protein trafficking and the maintenance of Golgi structure and homeostasis.
Proteins: Vps51;  Vps52;  Vps53;  Vps54

Other Organisms: Mouse (orthologs and functionally similar complex present)
Complex Function: Mediates mechanosensory transduction in the inner ear hair cells;  specifically contributing to the development and function of hair cell mechanotransduction channels required for hearing.
Proteins: TMC2 (core component);  potential association with TMIE;  LHFPL5;  and PCDH15 (as part of the broader mechanotransduction complex;  but TMC2 is the definitive core for human TMC2 complex)
Genes: TMC2 (primary constituent;  gene symbol TMC2);  TMIE (gene symbol TMIE);  LHFPL5 (gene symbol LHFPL5);  PCDH15 (gene symbol PCDH15) — as auxiliary partners in human mechanotransduction complexes

Complex Function: The TMC2 complex is implicated in mechanotransduction in cochlear hair cells;  contributing to the conversion of mechanical sound stimuli into electrical signals crucial for auditory perception.
Proteins: Transmembrane channel-like protein 2 (TMC2);  Transmembrane channel-like protein 1 (TMC1*) [Note: TMC2 can form a complex independently or with TMC1;  but TMC2-only complexes are functionally significant;  especially in early development.]

Other Organisms: Human (homolog present and implicated in inner ear function;  less characterized in Drosophila melanogaster;  C. elegans;  Saccharomyces cerevisiae)
Complex Function: The TMC2 complex is postulated to be a pore-forming component of the mechanoelectrical transduction (MET) channel in inner ear hair cells;  mediating mechanosensory ion flow essential for auditory transduction. In mice;  TMC2 is involved in early-stage MET channel function during cochlear development;  with later functional redundancy with TMC1.
Proteins: Transmembrane channel-like protein 2 (TMC2)

Organism: Human (Homo sapiens) – the 13 subunit eIF3 complex is most prominent in humans.
Other Organisms: Mouse (Mus musculus) – homologous 13 subunit structure;  C. elegans – eIF3 is also present as a multi-subunit complex;  but with variable subunit composition. Drosophila melanogaster and Saccharomyces cerevisiae have fewer subunits in their eIF3 complexes and are thus not included as having the full 13 subunit complex.
Complex Function: The eIF3 complex is essential for the initiation phase of eukaryotic translation. It facilitates the recruitment of the 40S ribosomal subunit to messenger RNA;  promotes the assembly of the 43S preinitiation complex;  aids in the scanning process for the start codon;  and prevents premature joining of the 60S subunit. In humans;  eIF3 is also implicated in reinitiation;  programmed mRNA selection;  and regulatory diverse cellular processes.
Proteins: EIF3A (eIF3 subunit A); EIF3B (eIF3 subunit B); EIF3C (eIF3 subunit C); EIF3D (eIF3 subunit D); EIF3E (eIF3 subunit E); EIF3F (eIF3 subunit F); EIF3G (eIF3 subunit G); EIF3H (eIF3 subunit H); EIF3I (eIF3 subunit I); EIF3J (eIF3 subunit J); EIF3K (eIF3 subunit K); EIF3L (eIF3 subunit L); EIF3M (eIF3 subunit M)
Genes: EIF3A (GeneID: 8661); EIF3B (GeneID: 8662); EIF3C (GeneID: 8663); EIF3D (GeneID: 8664); EIF3E (GeneID: 3646 / also known as INT6); EIF3F (GeneID: 8881); EIF3G (GeneID: 8666); EIF3H (GeneID: 8667); EIF3I (GeneID: 8668); EIF3J (GeneID: 8669); EIF3K (GeneID: 56902); EIF3L (GeneID: 55845); EIF3M (GeneID: 64935)

Complex Function: Central initiation factor in translation;  facilitates recruitment of the 40S ribosomal subunit to mRNA;  promotes subsequent assembly of the 43S preinitiation complex;  mediates other interactions required for translation initiation and reinitiation;  and influences the selection of start codons.
Proteins: eIF3 subunit A;  eIF3 subunit B;  eIF3 subunit C;  eIF3 subunit D;  eIF3 subunit E;  eIF3 subunit F;  eIF3 subunit G;  eIF3 subunit H;  eIF3 subunit I;  eIF3 subunit J;  eIF3 subunit K;  eIF3 subunit L;  eIF3 subunit M
Genes: EIF3A;  EIF3B;  EIF3C;  EIF3D;  EIF3E;  EIF3F;  EIF3G;  EIF3H;  EIF3I;  EIF3J;  EIF3K;  EIF3L;  EIF3M

Complex Function: eIF3 is a multi-subunit complex essential for the initiation of eukaryotic translation. It promotes the assembly of the pre-initiation complex (PIC) by binding the 40S ribosomal subunit;  stabilizes the ternary complex (eIF2-GTP-Met-tRNAi^Met);  aids recruitment of mRNA and other initiation factors;  and facilitates start codon recognition and mRNA scanning.

Complex Function: The Tip60 complex functions as a multi-subunit histone acetyltransferase (HAT) involved in acetylation of histones (notably H2A and H4);  DNA damage response;  chromatin remodeling;  transcriptional regulation;  and the control of gene expression;  especially in pathways of DNA repair and apoptosis.

Complex Function: Histone acetyltransferase (HAT) complex involved in acetylation of histones (notably H4 and H2A);  DNA damage response;  transcriptional regulation;  and chromatin remodeling;  specifically facilitating gene activation;  DNA repair;  and apoptosis.

Complex Function: A multiprotein histone acetyltransferase (HAT) complex that acetylates histone H4 and H2A;  playing a crucial role in chromatin remodeling;  gene transcription regulation;  DNA damage response;  and double-strand break repair via homologous recombination.

Complex Function: Multiprotein complex that acts as a regulator of the ubiquitin-proteasome pathway by controlling cullin-RING ligases (CRLs) via deneddylation;  also involved in DNA damage response;  cell cycle control;  and developmental processes.
