Proteins: Nuclear RNA export factor 1 (NXF1);  Nuclear transport factor 2-like export factor 1 (NXT1;  also known as p15)

Complex Name: NXF1-NXT1 mRNA nuclear export factor complex
Other Organisms: Mouse;  Drosophila melanogaster;  Saccharomyces cerevisiae (with functional homologues;  e.g.;  Mex67-Mtr2 in yeast;  Sbr-Nxt1 in fly)
Complex Function: Mediates the export of mRNA from the nucleus to the cytoplasm by interacting with mRNA-protein complexes and components of the nuclear pore complex (NPC);  serves as the principal mRNA export receptor.
Proteins: Nuclear RNA export factor 1 (NXF1);  Nuclear transport factor 2-like export factor 1 (NXT1)

Other Organisms: The MON1-CCZ1 complex is also found in Mouse (Mus musculus);  C. elegans;  Drosophila melanogaster;  and Saccharomyces cerevisiae;  with conserved functions;  however;  this analysis focuses on the human complex.
Complex Function: The MON1-CCZ1 complex functions as a guanine nucleotide exchange factor (GEF) specifically for the small GTPase RAB7;  facilitating the exchange of GDP for GTP on RAB7. This activation regulates maturation and fusion of late endosomes and lysosomes;  thereby playing a crucial role in endosomal trafficking;  autophagy;  and lysosome biogenesis.
Proteins: MON1B protein;  CCZ1 protein (note: in humans;  MON1 has paralogs MON1A and MON1B;  but MON1B is more studied in the context of this GEF complex)

Other Organisms: Mouse;  Drosophila melanogaster;  Saccharomyces cerevisiae;  C. elegans
Complex Function: Functions as a guanine nucleotide exchange factor (GEF) specifically for the small GTPase RAB7;  facilitating conversion of RAB7 from GDP- to GTP-bound form. It plays a crucial role in the endosomal maturation pathway;  promoting the transition from early endosomes (Rab5-positive) to late endosomes (Rab7-positive);  and is essential for proper trafficking and degradation of endocytosed cargo.
Proteins: MON1 homolog B;  CCZ1 homolog

Other Organisms: Mouse;  C. elegans;  Drosophila melanogaster;  Saccharomyces cerevisiae
Complex Function: Acts as a guanine nucleotide exchange factor (GEF) for the small GTPase RAB7;  mediating the conversion of late endosomes from a RAB5-positive to a RAB7-positive identity;  essential for endosomal maturation;  lysosomal trafficking;  and autophagosome-lysosome fusion.
Proteins: Monensin sensitivity protein 1 homolog (MON1B or MON1A);  CCZ1 homolog (CCZ1B or CCZ1A)

Other Organisms: Not found in Human;  Mouse;  C. elegans;  or Saccharomyces cerevisiae. The HipHop-HOAP complex is considered Drosophila-specific.
Complex Function: The HipHop-HOAP complex is essential for chromosome end-protection (telomere capping) in Drosophila melanogaster;  preventing recognition of chromosome ends as DNA breaks and suppressing inappropriate DNA repair and fusion.
Proteins: HOAP (HP1/ORC-Associated Protein);  HipHop

Complex Function: Essential for protecting Drosophila telomeres from recognition as DNA breaks;  preventing telomere fusion and degradation. Facilitates the assembly of the terminin complex;  critical for chromosome end capping;  distinguishing telomeres from double-strand breaks.
Proteins: HipHop protein;  HOAP (HP1/ORC-associated protein;  also known as HP1/ORC-associated protein)
Genes: hiphop;  cav (cav for caravaggio;  encodes HOAP)

Complex Function: The HipHop-HOAP complex is essential for telomere capping and protection in Drosophila melanogaster. It safeguards chromosome ends from being recognized as DNA breaks;  thereby preventing unwarranted DNA damage responses and end-to-end fusions. The complex facilitates the special telomere maintenance mechanism unique to Drosophila;  which involves transposon-mediated elongation rather than telomerase.
Proteins: HP1/ORC-associated protein (HOAP);  HP1-HOAP interacting protein (HipHop)
Genes: cav (cav for caviller;  encodes HOAP);  CG40127 (encodes HipHop)

Other Organisms: The highly analogous AF10/DOT1L complex exists in Human and Mouse;  but the ZFP-1(AF10)/DOT-1 complex with these specific orthologs and regulatory functions is most characterized in C. elegans.
Complex Function: Regulates H3K79 methylation and chromatin-mediated transcriptional control;  especially at heterochromatic and Pol II-regulated genes;  implicated in RNAi-dependent gene silencing and developmental gene expression regulation.
Proteins: ZFP-1 and DOT-1.1

Complex Function: This complex regulates transcription via chromatin modification;  notably by methylating histone H3 (at lysine 79);  thus influencing gene expression linked to RNAi and developmental processes.
Proteins: ZFP-1 (Zinc finger protein 1 homolog of AF10);  DOT-1.1 (Disruptor of telomeric silencing 1-like protein)

Complex Function: The ZFP-1(AF10)/DOT-1 complex in C. elegans functions as a chromatin-modifying complex that regulates gene expression through methylation of histone H3 at lysine 79 (H3K79);  thus influencing transcriptional elongation. It is important in modulating transcription of genes involved in development and stress response;  and acts primarily as a repressor in specific pathways.
Proteins: Zinc finger protein 1 (ZFP-1;  also known as AF10 homolog);  DOT-1 histone methyltransferase (CeDOT-1.1)

Other Organisms: No direct evidence supports the existence of this exact complex (comprising all three components: CED-3;  CED-4;  and MAC-1) in Human;  Mouse;  Drosophila melanogaster;  or Saccharomyces cerevisiae.
Complex Function: This complex is fundamental in the execution of programmed cell death (apoptosis) in C. elegans. It facilitates the activation of the caspase CED-3 by promoting its proteolytic maturation;  with CED-4 functioning as an adaptor. MAC-1 is proposed to be involved in modulating the assembly or activity of the CED-3/CED-4 complex;  although its mechanistic details are less characterized than those of CED-3 and CED-4.
Proteins: CED-3;  CED-4;  MAC-1

Complex Function: This protein complex is involved in the regulation and execution of apoptosis in the nematode Caenorhabditis elegans. CED-3 is a cysteine protease (caspase) that serves as the primary executioner of programmed cell death. CED-4;  an Apaf-1 homolog;  functions as an adaptor;  activating CED-3 by oligomerization. MAC-1 (also referred to as MAC-1 protein or mitochondrial apoptosis-induced channel-1 in C. elegans) enhances or facilitates the apoptotic process;  potentially via interactions with CED-4 and modulation of mitochondrial events during apoptosis.
Proteins: CED-3 caspase;  CED-4 apoptotic protease-activating factor homolog;  MAC-1 protein

Complex Function: This complex is fundamental in the apoptotic pathway of C. elegans;  where it mediates programmed cell death. ced-4;  a homolog of mammalian APAF-1;  facilitates the activation of ced-3;  a caspase protease. MAC-1 is thought to modulate the activity and/or assembly of the ced-3-ced-4 complex;  thus influencing apoptosis execution in the organism.
Proteins: Apoptotic protease CED-3;  Apoptotic protease activating factor CED-4;  MAC-1 protein

Other Organisms: Also found in Mouse;  C. elegans;  Drosophila melanogaster;  Saccharomyces cerevisiae
Complex Function: Mediates sister chromatid cohesion during mitosis by forming a ring-like structure that entraps sister chromatids;  ensuring proper chromosome segregation. Also involved in DNA repair and gene regulation during interphase.
Proteins: SMC1A;  SMC3;  RAD21;  STAG1 (SA1) and/or STAG2 (SA2)

Complex Function: Ensures sister chromatid cohesion during cell division by forming a ring structure around sister chromatids;  preventing premature separation. It also contributes to DNA repair;  transcription regulation;  and maintaining genomic stability.
Proteins: Structural maintenance of chromosomes proteins 1A and 3 (SMC1A;  SMC3);  RAD21 (also called SCC1);  Stromal antigen 1 and 2 (STAG1;  STAG2)

Other Organisms: Mouse;  Drosophila melanogaster;  Saccharomyces cerevisiae;  C. elegans
Complex Function: The nuclear mitotic cohesin complex is essential for sister chromatid cohesion during mitosis;  DNA repair;  and the regulation of gene expression. It forms a ring-shaped structure that entraps sister chromatids together;  ensuring proper chromosome segregation during cell division.
Proteins: Structural maintenance of chromosomes protein 1A (SMC1A);  Structural maintenance of chromosomes protein 3 (SMC3);  RAD21 cohesin complex component (RAD21);  Stromal antigen 1 (STAG1) or Stromal antigen 2 (STAG2)

Other Organisms: This specific complex composition (Atk-1/Akt-2/Sgk-1 together;  with these names and functions) is unique to C. elegans;  homologous proteins exist in Human (AKT1;  AKT2;  SGK1) and Mouse (Akt1;  Akt2;  Sgk1);  but there is no evidence that they function as a discrete complex in those organisms. No direct homologues or complexes exist in Drosophila melanogaster or Saccharomyces cerevisiae.
Complex Function: This complex forms part of a signaling module essential for regulating aging;  stress response;  metabolism;  and dauer formation in response to insulin/IGF-1 signaling in the nematode Caenorhabditis elegans. It consists of three closely related AGC protein kinases (Atk-1;  Akt-2;  Sgk-1) that act downstream of the phosphoinositide 3-kinase (PI3K) pathway. They collectively phosphorylate and inactivate the FOXO transcription factor DAF-16;  thus controlling longevity;  development;  and stress resistance.
Proteins: Atk-1 (Protein kinase B homolog 1); Akt-2 (Protein kinase B homolog 2); Sgk-1 (Serum/glucocorticoid regulated kinase homolog 1)

Complex Function: This complex mediates key signaling events in the insulin/PI3K pathway;  controlling lifespan;  metabolism;  development;  and stress response through phosphorylation of downstream targets;  including the FOXO transcription factor DAF-16.
Proteins: Protein kinase B (AKT-1);  Protein kinase B2 (AKT-2);  Serum- and glucocorticoid-inducible kinase homolog (SGK-1)

Complex Function: Mediates insulin/IGF-1 signaling;  regulating development;  metabolism;  stress resistance;  and lifespan;  primarily by transducing PI3K signaling to control downstream effectors;  including the FOXO transcription factor DAF-16.
Proteins: Protein kinase Akt-1;  Protein kinase Akt-2;  Protein kinase Sgk-1

Other Organisms: Mouse (Mus musculus) — analogues of this complex exist in mouse;  but the complex is most extensively characterized and studied in human.
Complex Function: Acts as a transcriptional repressor complex that regulates cell cycle progression by binding E2F-responsive elements in target gene promoters. Specifically;  RB1 (retinoblastoma protein) binds and represses E2F1/TFDP1-mediated transcription;  mainly inhibiting genes required for S phase entry and DNA replication.
Proteins: RB1 (Retinoblastoma-associated protein); E2F1 (E2F Transcription Factor 1); TFDP1 (Transcription Factor Dp-1)
Genes: RB1: RB1; E2F1: E2F1; TFDP1: TFDP1

Complex Function: Transcriptional repressor complex that regulates progression through the G1/S transition of the cell cycle by inhibiting E2F-target gene expression through chromatin remodeling and direct DNA binding.
Proteins: Retinoblastoma-associated protein (RB1);  Transcription factor E2F1;  Transcription factor Dp-1 (TFDP1)

Complex Function: This complex represses transcription of E2F target genes implicated in cell cycle progression;  particularly at the G1/S transition. RB1 binds E2F1 and TFDP1;  forming a complex that blocks E2F1-mediated transcriptional activation of genes required for DNA replication and S-phase entry.
Proteins: Retinoblastoma-associated protein (RB1);  Transcription factor E2F1;  Transcription factor Dp-1 (TFDP1)

Other Organisms: Not reported in Humans;  Mouse;  Drosophila melanogaster;  or Saccharomyces cerevisiae.
Complex Function: PETISCO is a germline-specific protein complex in Caenorhabditis elegans required for the biogenesis of 21U-RNAs (piRNAs);  which are crucial for genome regulation and transposon silencing. The PID-1 variant facilitates primary piRNA precursor (21U-RNA) processing.
Proteins: IFE-3;  TOFU-6;  PID-3;  ERH-2;  PID-1

Other Organisms: N/A (PETISCO as a complex is C. elegans-specific among the listed organisms)
Complex Function: The PETISCO;  pid-1 variant is a protein complex involved in piRNA biogenesis;  specifically in 21U RNA (piRNA) precursor processing in the germline;  crucial for genome integrity in the nematode. The pid-1-containing PETISCO variant is active in piRNA processing during germ cell development.
Proteins: PID-1;  TOFU-6;  ERH-2;  and IFE-3

Complex Function: The PETISCO complex (PID-1-dependent variant) is essential for the biogenesis of 21U-RNAs (piRNAs) in the germline of C. elegans;  serving a role in the processing of piRNA precursors and safeguarding genome integrity by silencing transposable elements during germ cell development.
Proteins: PID-3;  ERH-2;  TOFU-6;  IFE-3;  PID-1

Other Organisms: Not found in Human;  Mouse;  Drosophila melanogaster;  or Saccharomyces cerevisiae. PETISCO complex is currently only characterized in C. elegans;  canonical homologs and functionality have not been identified in the other listed organisms.
Complex Function: The PETISCO;  tost-1 variant in Caenorhabditis elegans is involved in piRNA precursor processing;  facilitating the maturation and stabilization of piRNA (21U-RNA) precursors which are crucial for genome defense in the germline. The tost-1 variant refers to the version of the PETISCO complex specifically including the protein TOST-1;  influencing the complexs stability and RNA-binding versatility.
Proteins: PID-3;  TOFU-6;  ERH-2;  IFE-3;  TOST-1

Other Organisms: N/A (no homologous PETISCO complex described in Human;  Mouse;  Drosophila melanogaster;  or Saccharomyces cerevisiae)
Complex Function: PETISCO (Piwi-Expressed Transcript Isoform Complex) is involved in piRNA (21U-RNA) biogenesis;  a pathway essential for genome defense;  germline development;  and transposon silencing. The tost-1 variant refers to a specific form including the TOST-1 protein;  believed to modulate complex function during early embryogenesis or under particular developmental contexts.
Proteins: PID-3;  ERH-2;  IFE-3;  TOFU-6;  and in the tost-1 variant;  TOST-1

Complex Function: PETISCO (Processing of Engaged Transcripts in the SILencing COmplex) is a protein complex crucial for piRNA biogenesis;  a pathway protecting the genome from transposon activity through small RNA-mediated silencing in the germline. The tost-1 variant denotes the replacement of canonical PID-1 with TOST-1;  altering complex specificity and targeting non-coding RNA biogenesis necessary for embryonic development.
Proteins: PID-3;  TOFU-6;  ERH-2;  IFE-3;  TOST-1

Other Organisms: Human;  Mouse;  C. elegans;  Drosophila melanogaster
Complex Function: The Ndc80 complex is a conserved kinetochore component essential for the attachment of spindle microtubules to chromosomes during mitosis;  facilitating chromosome alignment and segregation. In Saccharomyces cerevisiae;  it also plays a critical role in kinetochore-microtubule coupling and the spindle assembly checkpoint.
Proteins: Ndc80p (also called Hec1p in some literature);  Nuf2p;  Spc24p;  Spc25p

Other Organisms: Mouse;  Saccharomyces cerevisiae;  C. elegans;  Drosophila melanogaster
Complex Function: The Ndc80 complex is an essential component of the outer kinetochore that mediates attachment between spindle microtubules and kinetochores during mitosis. It ensures proper chromosome alignment and segregation during cell division.
Proteins: Kinetochore protein NDC80 homolog;  Kinetochore protein NUF2 homolog;  Kinetochore protein SPC24;  Kinetochore protein SPC25

Other Organisms: Mouse;  C. elegans;  Drosophila melanogaster;  Saccharomyces cerevisiae
Complex Function: The Ndc80 complex is a crucial component of the kinetochore;  mediating direct attachment between microtubules and chromosomes to ensure proper chromosome segregation during mitosis. It is required for stable kinetochore-microtubule attachments and is essential for accurate chromosome alignment and segregation.
Proteins: Ndc80 (also known as Hec1);  Nuf2;  Spc24;  Spc25

Other Organisms: Also found in Mus musculus (Mouse);  Caenorhabditis elegans;  Drosophila melanogaster;  and Saccharomyces cerevisiae (conserved across all five listed organisms;  though individual subunit identities and gene names can differ).
Complex Function: Essential component of the inner kinetochore;  it functions as a key linker between the centromere (via the constitutive centromere-associated network;  CCAN) and the outer kinetochore (Ndc80 complex);  thereby promoting accurate microtubule-chromosome attachment during mitosis and ensuring faithful chromosome segregation.
Proteins: MIS12;  DSN1;  NSL1;  PMF1 (also known as MIS12 complex subunit 4;  or hNnf1)

Other Organisms: Mouse;  C. elegans;  Drosophila melanogaster;  Saccharomyces cerevisiae
Complex Function: The Mis12 complex is an essential component of the kinetochore;  mediating interactions between centromeric chromatin and outer kinetochore microtubule-binding components. It is critical for proper chromosome alignment and segregation during mitosis.
Proteins: Mis12;  NSL1;  DSN1;  PMF1

Other Organisms: Mouse;  Drosophila melanogaster;  C. elegans;  Saccharomyces cerevisiae
Complex Function: The Mis12 complex is a core component of the kinetochore;  a multiprotein structure assembled on centromeric chromatin during mitosis. Its primary function is to link inner kinetochore proteins (constitutive centromere-associated network;  CCAN) with the outer kinetochore (the KMN network);  contributing to proper microtubule attachment and faithful chromosome segregation during cell division.
Proteins: MIS12 (MIS12 kinetochore complex component);  DSN1 (MIS12 complex subunit DSN1);  NSL1 (MIS12 complex subunit NSL1);  PMF1 (MIS12 complex subunit PMF1;  also known as MIS12 complex subunit WD repeat-containing protein 62;  and referred to as NNF1 in some literature)

Other Organisms: Human;  Mouse;  Drosophila melanogaster;  C. elegans
Complex Function: The THO complex is involved in the coupling of transcription elongation with mRNA processing and export. It plays a key role in maintaining genome stability by preventing the accumulation of R-loops and also helps in the efficient packaging of mRNA into messenger ribonucleoprotein particles (mRNPs) for export from the nucleus.
Proteins: Tho2;  Hpr1;  Mft1;  Thp2;  Tex1

Other Organisms: Human;  Mouse;  Drosophila melanogaster;  C. elegans
Complex Function: The THO complex is a multi-protein nuclear complex that plays a crucial role in transcription elongation;  mRNA export from the nucleus;  and genome stability. It acts as a key player in coupling transcription with mRNA processing and export.
Proteins: Hpr1;  Tho2;  Mft1;  Thp2;  Tex1

Other Organisms: Human;  Mouse;  Drosophila melanogaster (THO complex is conserved;  but analysis here is specific to S. cerevisiae)
Complex Function: The THO complex is involved in coupling transcription elongation with mRNA processing and export;  ensuring genomic stability by minimizing R-loop accumulation;  it is essential for efficient mRNA export from the nucleus.
Proteins: Hpr1;  Tho2;  Mft1;  Thp2;  Tex1

Other Organisms: Not found in Human;  Mouse;  C. elegans;  or Drosophila melanogaster as this specific four-component complex.
Complex Function: Mediates vesicle fusion at the prevacuolar (endosomal) compartment;  enabling efficient protein trafficking from the Golgi to endosomes in the cell. Essential for proper endomembrane system organization and cargo delivery.
Proteins: Tlg2p;  Vti1p;  Tlg1p;  Snc2p

Complex Function: Mediates vesicle fusion at the endosomal compartment;  crucial for intracellular trafficking in the endosomal system;  particularly for the fusion of vesicles with the late endosome or prevacuolar compartment.
Proteins: Target membrane SNARE protein Tlg2p;  vesicle transport v-SNARE Vti1p;  syntaxin-like t-SNARE Tlg1p;  synaptobrevin-like SNARE SNC2p

Other Organisms: N/A (The canonical TLG2-VTI1-TLG1-SNC2 combination is specific to S. cerevisiae;  although SNARE family homologs exist in other eukaryotes.)
Complex Function: This endosomal SNARE complex mediates membrane fusion at the late endosome and prevacuolar compartment;  facilitating vesicular trafficking within the endomembrane system.
Proteins: Tlg2p;  Vti1p;  Tlg1p;  Snc2p

Other Organisms: None (the Ste12/Dig1/Dig2 complex is unique to Saccharomyces cerevisiae among the listed organisms;  homologous complexes with direct functional/structural equivalence are not present in Human;  Mouse;  C. elegans;  or Drosophila melanogaster).
Complex Function: This complex regulates transcription in response to pheromone signaling and filamentous growth pathways. Ste12 is a transcription factor that activates gene expression related to mating and filamentous growth. Dig1 and Dig2 are negative regulators that bind Ste12;  modulating its DNA-binding activity and its recruitment to gene promoters;  especially under conditions of MAPK pathway stimulation.
Proteins: Ste12; Dig1; Dig2
Genes: STE12 (YHR084W) – encodes Ste12 protein; DIG1 (YPL049C;  also known as RST1) – encodes Dig1 protein; DIG2 (YHR043C;  also known as RST2) – encodes Dig2 protein

Complex Function: Transcription factor complex responsible for regulating gene expression during mating and filamentous growth in response to pheromone signaling;  mediates MAPK pathway-dependent activation of downstream target genes by Ste12;  with Dig1 and Dig2 serving as negative regulators modulating Ste12 DNA binding and transcriptional activity.
Proteins: Ste12;  Dig1;  Dig2

Other Organisms: N/A (Complex is unique to S. cerevisiae among the listed organisms;  no characterized orthologous complex in Human;  Mouse;  Drosophila melanogaster;  or C. elegans.)
Complex Function: The Ste12/Dig1/Dig2 complex is a transcriptional regulatory complex fundamental for the control of mating and filamentation gene expression in response to pheromone signaling and nutrient limitation. Ste12 is the core transcription factor;  while Dig1 and Dig2 modulate its activity by repressing or fine-tuning Ste12 DNA binding and interaction with cofactors.
Proteins: Ste12;  Dig1;  Dig2

Other Organisms: Homo sapiens;  Mus musculus;  Drosophila melanogaster (TRAPP II homologs present;  but composition and subunit makeup have diverged)
Complex Function: The TRAPP II complex is a multi-subunit tethering complex involved in mediating vesicle trafficking;  particularly between the Golgi apparatus and endosomes;  and within the late Golgi compartments. It plays a crucial role in vesicle tethering prior to membrane fusion;  thus ensuring proper protein sorting and trafficking.
Proteins: Trs120p; Trs130p; Trs65p; Trs33p; Bet3p; Bet5p; Trs20p; Trs23p; Trs31p; Trs85p (sometimes considered part of TRAPP III;  but can associate); TRAPP II is defined by the presence of Trs120p;  Trs130p;  and Trs65p;  which distinguish it from TRAPP I.*
Genes: TRS120 (YDR246W); TRS130 (YPL180W); TRS65 (YDR373W); TRS33 (YKR068C); BET3 (YHR097C); BET5 (YPL198W); TRS20 (YLR407W); TRS23 (YPL029W); TRS31 (YNL051W); TRS85 (YMR218C) (associated;  not core to all functions)

Complex Function: The TRAPP II complex is a multi-subunit tethering complex crucial for vesicle-mediated transport;  specifically acting as a guanine nucleotide exchange factor (GEF) for Ypt1/Rab1 and Ypt31/32/Rab11 GTPases;  facilitating intra-Golgi and endosome-to-Golgi trafficking.
Proteins: TRS120 (Trs120p);  TRS130 (Trs130p);  TRS65 (Trs65p);  TRS33 (Trs33p);  BET3 (Bet3p);  BET5 (Bet5p);  TRS23 (Trs23p);  TRS20 (Trs20p);  TRS31 (Trs31p)
Genes: TRS120;  TRS130;  TRS65;  TRS33;  BET3;  BET5;  TRS23;  TRS20;  TRS31

Other Organisms: Human;  Drosophila melanogaster;  C. elegans;  Mouse
Complex Function: Acts as a multimeric tethering complex involved in vesicle-mediated transport at the Golgi apparatus;  specifically mediating intra-Golgi and endosome-to-Golgi trafficking. Functions as a guanine nucleotide exchange factor (GEF) for the Rab GTPase Ypt1p and Ypt31/32p;  facilitating specific trafficking events within the Golgi.
Proteins: Bet3p;  Bet5p;  Trs23p;  Trs20p;  Trs31p;  Trs33p;  Trs65p;  Trs120p;  Trs130p;  Trs85p (minor/associating component).
Genes: BET3;  BET5;  TRS23 (YLR097C);  TRS20 (YOL018C);  TRS31 (YDR246W);  TRS33 (YNL079C);  TRS65 (YMR017W);  TRS120 (YDR407C);  TRS130 (YDR407C);  TRS85 (YGL182C).

Complex Function: The CCM complex is a multiprotein structure critical for the maintenance of endothelial cell-cell junctions and vascular integrity in humans. It regulates signaling pathways involved in cytoskeletal organization;  barrier function;  and angiogenesis;  with dysfunction leading to cerebral cavernous malformations;  characterized by clusters of dilated cerebral blood vessels prone to hemorrhage.
Proteins: CCM1 (KRIT1);  CCM2 (MGC4607;  also called malcavernin);  CCM3 (PDCD10)

Other Organisms: Mouse (orthologous complex is present);  C. elegans (homologous proteins present;  but not a fully conserved complex);  Drosophila melanogaster (partial conservation);  Saccharomyces cerevisiae (not present)
Complex Function: The CCM (Cerebral Cavernous Malformations) complex is critical for maintaining vascular integrity and endothelial cell–cell junction stability. It prevents abnormal vascular morphogenesis and permeability;  which are hallmarks of cerebral cavernous malformations in the central nervous system.
Proteins: Cerebral cavernous malformations 1 protein (CCM1/KRIT1);  CCM2 (OSM;  malcavernin);  CCM3 (PDCD10)

Complex Function: The CCM complex is involved in the maintenance of vascular integrity in the central nervous system. It functions in endothelial cell-to-cell junction stability and modulates signaling pathways critical for angiogenesis and blood-brain barrier stability. Disruption of the complex leads to cerebral cavernous malformations;  characterized by clusters of dilated;  thin-walled blood vessels in the brain.
Proteins: CCM1 (Krev interaction trapped protein 1);  CCM2 (malcavernin);  and CCM3 (programmed cell death 10 [PDCD10])
Genes: KRIT1 (for CCM1);  CCM2 (for CCM2);  PDCD10 (for CCM3)

Complex Function: mu-Calpain is a calcium-dependent;  non-lysosomal cysteine protease complex involved in cytoskeletal remodeling;  signal transduction;  and apoptosis via specific limited proteolysis of targeted substrates. It plays critical roles in cellular migration;  cell cycle progression;  and synaptic plasticity.
Proteins: Calpain-1 catalytic subunit (large subunit;  ~80 kDa); Calpain small subunit 1 (regulatory subunit;  ~28 kDa)
Genes: CAPN1 (encodes Calpain-1 large/catalytic subunit); CAPNS1 (encodes Calpain small subunit 1)

Complex Function: Ca2+-dependent;  non-lysosomal cysteine protease complex involved in cytoskeletal remodeling;  signal transduction;  and regulation of apoptosis by targeted limited proteolysis of specific substrates.
Proteins: m-calpain catalytic subunit (CAPN1);  calpain small regulatory subunit (CAPNS1)

Complex Function: The mu-Calpain complex is a calcium-dependent;  non-lysosomal cysteine protease responsible for limited proteolysis of substrates involved in cytoskeletal remodeling;  signal transduction;  and apoptosis;  it is critically involved in processes such as cell motility and cell cycle progression.
Proteins: Calpain-1 catalytic subunit (mu-type;  also termed mu-calpain large subunit);  Calpain small subunit 1 (common regulatory subunit shared with calpain-2)
Genes: CAPN1 (calpain 1;  catalytic subunit);  CAPNS1 (calpain small subunit 1)

Other Organisms: Mouse (Mus musculus);  C. elegans;  Drosophila melanogaster;  Saccharomyces cerevisiae
Complex Function: The GINS complex is essential for the initiation and progression of DNA replication. It forms part of the CMG (Cdc45-MCM-GINS) helicase complex;  facilitating the unwinding of DNA and recruitment of replication factors during S phase.
Proteins: GINS1 (also known as SLD5); GINS2 (also known as PSF2); GINS3 (also known as PSF3); GINS4 (also known as PSF1)
Genes: GINS1 gene (chromosome 20p11); GINS2 gene (chromosome 16q21); GINS3 gene (chromosome 16p13.3); GINS4 gene (chromosome 8q24.3)

Other Organisms: Mouse;  C. elegans;  Drosophila melanogaster;  Saccharomyces cerevisiae
Complex Function: The GINS complex is essential for the initiation and progression of DNA replication. It acts as part of the eukaryotic replicative helicase (CMG complex) that unwinds double-stranded DNA at the replication fork;  permitting synthesis of new DNA strands.
Proteins: GINS complex subunit 1 (Sld5);  GINS complex subunit 2 (Psf2);  GINS complex subunit 3 (Psf3);  GINS complex subunit 4 (Psf1)

Other Organisms: Mouse;  Drosophila melanogaster;  Saccharomyces cerevisiae;  C. elegans
Complex Function: Essential component of the eukaryotic DNA replication machinery;  specifically functioning within the CMG (Cdc45-MCM-GINS) helicase complex to initiate and elongate replication forks during S phase. GINS is critical for helicase activation and replisome progression.
Proteins: GINS complex subunit 1 (Psf1);  GINS complex subunit 2 (Psf2);  GINS complex subunit 3 (Psf3);  GINS complex subunit 4 (Sld5)

Other Organisms: Mus musculus (Mouse);  Drosophila melanogaster;  Caenorhabditis elegans;  Saccharomyces cerevisiae
Complex Function: The CMG helicase complex functions as the replicative DNA helicase that unwinds double-stranded DNA ahead of the replication fork during S phase;  ensuring proper DNA replication initiation and elongation.
Proteins: MCM2;  MCM3;  MCM4;  MCM5;  MCM6;  MCM7;  CDC45;  GINS1 (Sld5);  GINS2 (Psf2);  GINS3 (Psf3);  GINS4 (Psf1)
Genes: MCM2;  MCM3;  MCM4;  MCM5;  MCM6;  MCM7;  CDC45;  GINS1;  GINS2;  GINS3;  GINS4

Other Organisms: Mouse;  Drosophila melanogaster;  Saccharomyces cerevisiae;  C. elegans
Complex Function: The CMG (Cdc45-Mcm2-7-GINS) helicase complex is essential for the unwinding of duplex DNA at replication forks during S phase;  enabling replication fork progression and DNA synthesis.

Other Organisms: The core function and composition of the ATP4A-ATP4B complex are highly conserved;  and similar complexes can be found in Mouse.
Complex Function: The ATP4A-ATP4B complex;  also known as the gastric H+/K+ ATPase;  primarily functions in the stomach to exchange potassium ions (K+) for hydrogen ions (H+) across the gastric epithelium;  driving acidification of the stomach contents. This process is essential for digestion and maintaining an acidic environment that is critical for activating digestive enzymes.
Proteins: The complex is composed of two main subunits - ATP4A (Alpha subunit) and ATP4B (Beta subunit).
Genes: The ATP4A protein corresponds to the ATP4A gene;  and the ATP4B protein corresponds to the ATP4B gene in humans.

Functions downstream of the molecular circadian clock in pacemaker neurons to promote behavioral rhythmicity.
Proteins: Potassium-transporting ATPase alpha chain 1;  Potassium-transporting ATPase subunit beta; Protein unc-80 homolog;  Narrow abdomen isoform F;  Uncoordinated 79 isoform B

Complex Function: The cytochrome bc1 complex;  also known as Complex III;  is a critical component of the mitochondrial electron transport chain. It facilitates the transfer of electrons from ubiquinol to cytochrome c while simultaneously translocating protons across the mitochondrial inner membrane. This process helps create the proton gradient required for ATP synthesis.
Proteins: In Saccharomyces cerevisiae;  the cytochrome bc1 complex is composed of multiple subunits;  including cytochrome b;  cytochrome c1;  and the Rieske iron-sulfur protein;  among others.
Genes: Key genes encoding the proteins of the cytochrome bc1 complex in Saccharomyces cerevisiae include CYT1 (cytochrome c1);  QCR2 (core protein 2);  COR1 (core protein 1);  RIP1 (Rieske iron-sulfur protein);  and COB (cytochrome b).
